The '''Bhutta''' are a community found in Pakistan and India. They may be classified as either [[Jat]]<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nV71AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA130|title=Re-Thinking Punjab: The Construction of Siraiki Identity |first=Hussain Ahmad |last=Khan |editor-first=Samina |editor-last=Choonara |publisher=Research and Publication Centre, National College of Arts, Lahore |year=2004 |isbn=978-9-69862-309-8 |page=130}}</ref> or [[Rajput]].<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iKsqzB4P1ioC&lpg=PA185 |title=Rajasthan}}</ref> They are predominantly [[Muslim]] with large [[Hindu]] and small [[Sikh]] minorities, respectively.{{cn|date=December 2017}}

== Bhutta Family in Pakistan ==
the Bhutta tribe conquered a large part of what is today [[Dera Ghazi Khan District]] and established themselves at [[Jampur]] .

== Bhutta Family in Pakistan ==
the Bhutta tribe conquered a large part of what is today [[Bahawalpur|[Bahawalpur District]]] and established themselves at [[Uch|Uch Sharief]] .

